04689nam a22006015i 9780300157826DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221997ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001578267 a10.12987/97803001578262doi  a(DE-B1597)625712  a(OCoLC)1322125454  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aPR1964b.K45 1997eb 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a821/.12221 aKeiser, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCourtly Desire and Medieval Homophobia :bThe Legitimation of Sexual Pleasure in `Cleanness` and Its Contexts /cElizabeth Keiser. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Narrative Theology of Cleanness and the Aesthetic Ethics of Thomas Aquinas -- t2 Homophobic Wrath and Paradisal Pleasure -- t3 Educating Love: Nature as Sexual Norm in Cleanness and Alain's Complaint -- t4 The Sexual Ethics of Cleanness and Thomas Aquinas on Temperance -- t5 Revising the Complaint: Desire in the Roman as Context for Cleanness -- t6 Privileging the Feminine: Courtly Revisions of Masculinity -- t7 Homosocial Bondings with God and Christ -- t8 Theopoetic Coherence: Cleanness among Its Manuscript Companions -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the first comprehensive study of Cleanness and its medieval contexts, Elizabeth B. Keiser shows how this fourteenth-century religious poem legitimates erotic pleasure as natural apart from procreative justification and thus represents a unique moment in western culture. She argues that Cleanness sacralizes heterosexual erotic play while condemning male homosexual love as profaning the Creator`s workmanship and his nature. To situate the poem in the context of medieval homophobic constructions of nature as the basis of sexual norms, this book compares Cleanness`s concepts of sexual desire and deviance with those of its literary and theological antecedents, including Thomas Aquinas`s discourse on temperance, Alain de Lille`s Complaint of Nature, and Jean de Meun`s Romance of the Rose. Cleanness is shown to be unconventionally affirmative of loveplay and other refinements of courtly artifice. Keiser explores the broad intellectual and social consequences of this celebration of late medieval masculine ideals and analyzes how the poet`s class-specific aesthetic sensibility underlies a theologically and ethically flawed revisionist history of the biblical Creator`s love affair with the creation. These limitations shed interesting light on Cleanness`s relation to its theologically more complex and structurally more sophisticated companion poems-Patience, Sir Gawain and the Green Knight, and Pearl.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChristian poetry, English (Middle)xHistory and criticism. 0aCourtly love in literature. 0aDesire in literature. 0aGay men in literature. 0aHomophobia in literature. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezEnglandxHistory. 0aHomosexualityxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aPleasurexReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aSexxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311053801440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015782640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300157826423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300157826/original  a978-3-11-0